paragraphs.text:
%md
### Avoiding failed payments and involuntary churn

You have a hunch that weakening profits may be due to the company selling to non-optimal customers;  customers who  have good enough credit to purchase "big ticket items" e.g. large televisions, appliances and durable goods on payment credit cards and payment plans but then fail to complete all their payments and have to return the purchased goods. The company takes a loss and has to resell the items at a discount as "used".

In your data assembled inside Oracle Autonomous Database, you have over 100 variables to consider to understand your data and to find these hidden patterns and eventually to build predictive models that target these "Good_Credit" better customers.  You wants to first explore  data using simple charts and graphs, but then move onto using Oracle Machine Learning's powerful algorithms to automatically sift through her data to find patterns, new insights and to make predictions that target her best customers--those who have both good enough credit and are able to complete all the payments.  

Let's take a look.

Contributors:   Charlie berger, Derrick Cameron, Dhvani Sheth, Siddesh C Prabhu Dev Ujjni

paragraphs.text:
%md
### Target "Good_Credit" Customers Who Can Make All Payments and Don't Involuntary Churn

You want to avoid  customers who fail to make payments and  involuntarily churn.   You will be using Oracle Machine Learning's classification models in Autonomous Database. In the CREDIT_SCORING_100K dataset, you have tagged the disearable customers as "Good_Credit" in the CREDIT_SCORING_100K table. Those who either have lower credit or have failed to keep up with their payments and have involuntarily churned you have labeled as "Other_Credit" customers. You want to build Oracle Machine Learning predictive models that target  "Good_Credit" customer and can generate insights about them.  

Let's get started!

paragraphs.title: Review all customers by MARITAL_STATUS
paragraphs.text:
%sql 

-- This shows a pie chart of OCCUPATION from a choice of a few selected attributes from CREDIT_SCORING_100K.

SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, AGE, INCOME, TENURE, LOAN_TYPE, LOAN_AMOUNT, OCCUPATION, MARITAL_STATUS
FROM CREDIT_SCORING_100K_V WHERE ROWNUM < 1000;

paragraphs.title: Apply model to new customers to make predictions about customers who are likely to be "GOOD_CREDIT" and complete their payments
paragraphs.text:
%sql 

-- This will show the top predictive attributes 

SELECT A.CUSTOMER_ID
	, A.PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN
	, B.AGE, B.INCOME, B.TENURE, B.LOAN_TYPE, B.LOAN_AMOUNT, B.OCCUPATION, B.EDUCATION_LEVEL, B.MARITAL_STATUS
FROM (SELECT * FROM (SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, ROUND(PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN *100,2) PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN FROM (SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, PREDICTION_PROBABILITY(N1_CLASS_MODEL, NULL USING *) PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN FROM CREDIT_SCORING_NEW_CUST_V))) A
, CREDIT_SCORING_100K_V B
WHERE A.CUSTOMER_ID = B.CUSTOMER_ID 
ORDER BY A.PROB_CREDIT_SCORE_BIN DESC

paragraphs.title: Create a new table CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS
paragraphs.text:
%script

-- create new table with model predictions and probabilities so we can view in other data visualization tools

CREATE TABLE CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS AS 
SELECT A.CUSTOMER_ID
	, A.PROB_GOOD_CREDIT
	, B.AGE, B.INCOME, B.TENURE, B.LOAN_TYPE, B.LOAN_AMOUNT, B.OCCUPATION, B.EDUCATION_LEVEL, B.MARITAL_STATUS
FROM (SELECT * FROM (SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, ROUND(PROB_GOOD_CREDIT *100,2) PROB_GOOD_CREDIT FROM (SELECT CUSTOMER_ID, PREDICTION_PROBABILITY(N1_CLASS_MODEL, 'Good Credit' USING *) PROB_GOOD_CREDIT FROM CREDIT_SCORING_NEW_CUST_V))) A
, CREDIT_SCORING_100K_V B
WHERE A.CUSTOMER_ID = B.CUSTOMER_ID

msg.data: Table CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS created.

paragraphs.title: Review CREDIT_SCORING_NEW_PREDICTIONS  sorting "GOOD_CREDIT" customers by PROB_GOOD_CREDIT
paragraphs.text:
%sql 

-- Score and rank new customers that are a professional, married, and borrowing for education (in this case).  You can substitute or add other filters.

SELECT * FROM CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS 
ORDER BY RANK() OVER (ORDER BY PROB_GOOD_CREDIT DESC);

paragraphs.title: "What-if" real-time predictions on a single record
paragraphs.text:
%sql

-- Try "what-if" analysis to see real-time predictions by running this query, and then change WEALTH from 'Rich" to 'Poor" (in both parts of the query) and re-run the query to see lower probability of customer being a "Good_Credit" customer who will likley complete all payments. 
-- Hint: When the user specifies using "FROM DUAL", OML will use the mean and mode values for all other attributes used in the model.


SELECT 
PREDICTION(N1_CLASS_MODEL USING 'Rich' AS WEALTH, 2000 AS INCOME, 'Gold' AS CUSTOMER_VALUE_SEGMENT) PREDICTION,
ROUND(100*PREDICTION_PROBABILITY(N1_CLASS_MODEL, 'Good Credit' USING 'Rich' AS WEALTH, 2000 AS INCOME, 'Gold' AS CUSTOMER_VALUE_SEGMENT),1) LIKELY_PREDICTION_CORRECT_PCNT
FROM DUAL;

paragraphs.title: Update CUSTOMER_SCORING_100_V View
paragraphs.text:
%script
-- Note: Now that we have our predictions, we want to create a new table that includes the CREDIT_SCORE_100K data with the Oracle Machine Learning generated new predictions and probabilities.

CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW CREDIT_SCORING_100K_PREDICT_V AS SELECT A.PROB_GOOD_CREDIT, B.*
FROM CREDIT_SCORE_NEW_PREDICTIONS A, ADMIN.CREDIT_SCORING_100K B
WHERE A.CUSTOMER_ID = B.CUSTOMER_ID;
